Step 3: Train a model using AutoGluon’s Tabular Prediction¶

Requirements:

  • We are predicting count, so it is the label we are setting.
  • Ignore casual and registered columns as they are also not present in the test dataset.
  • Use the root_mean_squared_error as the metric to use for evaluation.
  • Set a time limit of 10 minutes (600 seconds).
  • Use the preset best_quality to focus on creating the best model.
In [ ]:
predictor = TabularPredictor(label='count', eval_metric='root_mean_squared_error').fit(
    train_data=train.drop(['casual', 'registered'], axis=1),
    time_limit=600,
    presets='best_quality')

In [ ]:
# Feature that categorizes morning, lunch, and evening rush hour, 7-9am, 11am-1pm, and 5-6pm
def categorize_rush_hours(hour):
    morning = range(7, 10)
    lunch = range(11, 14)
    evening = range(17, 19)

    if hour in morning:
        return 1
    if hour in lunch:
        return 2
    if hour in evening:
        return 3
    return 0

train['rush_hours'] = train['hour'].apply(categorize_rush_hours)
test['rush_hours'] = test['hour'].apply(categorize_rush_hours)

def categorize_temp(temp):
    cold = 16
    hot = 25

    if temp < cold:
        return 1
    if temp >= cold and temp < hot:
        return 2
    if temp >= hot:
        return 3

train['temp_cat'] = train['temp'].apply(categorize_temp)
test['temp_cat'] = test['temp'].apply(categorize_temp)
In [ ]:
train['windspeed'].hist();
In [ ]:
def categorize_wind(windspeed):
    windy = 12
    very_windy = 25

    if windspeed < windy:
        return 0
    if windspeed >= windy and windspeed < very_windy:
        return 1
    if windspeed >= very_windy:
        return 2

train['wind_cat'] = train['windspeed'].apply(categorize_wind)
test['wind_cat'] = test['windspeed'].apply(categorize_wind)
In [ ]:
train['humidity'].hist();
In [ ]:
def categorize_humidity(humidity):
    not_humid = 20
    humid = 75

    if humidity < not_humid:
        return 0
    if humidity >= not_humid and humidity < humid:
        return 1
    return 2

train['humid_cat'] = train['humidity'].apply(categorize_humidity)
test['humid_cat'] = test['humidity'].apply(categorize_humidity)

Make category types for these so models know they are not just numbers¶

  • AutoGluon originally sees these as ints, but in reality they are int representations of a category.
  • Setting the dtype to category will classify these as categories in AutoGluon.
In [ ]:
train["season"] = train["season"].astype('category')
train["weather"] = train["weather"].astype('category')
train["rush_hours"] = train["rush_hours"].astype('category')
train["temp_cat"] = train["temp_cat"].astype('category')
train["wind_cat"] = train["wind_cat"].astype('category')
train["humid_cat"] = train["humid_cat"].astype('category')

test["season"] = test["season"].astype('category')
test["weather"] = test["weather"].astype('category')
test["rush_hours"] = test["rush_hours"].astype('category')
test["temp_cat"] = test["temp_cat"].astype('category')
test["wind_cat"] = test["wind_cat"].astype('category')
test["humid_cat"] = test["humid_cat"].astype('category')

def submit_top5(predictor, test, file_prefix, msg_prefix):
    model_to_use = predictor.leaderboard().model
    for model in model_to_use[:5]:
        prediction_top5 = predictor.predict(test, model=model)
        prediction_top5[prediction_top5 < 0] = 0
        submission_top5 = pd.read_csv('sampleSubmission.csv')
        submission_top5["count"] = prediction_top5
        filename = f"{file_prefix}_{model}.csv".replace('/', '_')
        submission_top5.to_csv(filename, index=False)
        !kaggle competitions submit -c bike-sharing-demand -f {filename} -m "{msg_prefix} {model}"


def get_submission_score(predictor):
    output_k = !kaggle competitions submissions -c bike-sharing-demand | tail -n +1 | head -n 9
    submission_results = [float(output_k[i].split()[-1]) for i in range(6, 1, -1)]

    leaderboard = predictor.leaderboard()[:5]
    leaderboard['score_val'] = leaderboard['score_val'] * -1
    leaderboard['subm_score'] = submission_results

    eval_score = leaderboard['score_val'][0]
    kaggle_score = sorted(submission_results)[0]

    return leaderboard, eval_score, kaggle_score


def plot_eval_and_kaggle_scores(leaderboard, path):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=2, figsize=(20,6))
    leaderboard.plot(kind='bar', x='model', y='score_val', ax = axes[0], subplots=True)
    leaderboard.plot(kind='bar', x='model', y='subm_score', color='red', ax = axes[1], subplots=True)
    fig.savefig(path)

Step 6: Hyper parameter optimization¶

  • There are many options for hyper parameter optimization.
  • Options are to change the AutoGluon higher level parameters or the individual model hyperparameters.
  • The hyperparameters of the models themselves that are in AutoGluon. Those need the hyperparameter and hyperparameter_tune_kwargs arguments.
In [ ]:
predictor_new_hpo_time = TabularPredictor(label='count', eval_metric='root_mean_squared_error').fit(

models_to_train = ['NN_TORCH', 'GBM', 'CAT', 'XGB', 'FASTAI', 'RF', 'XT', 'KNN']
solo_model_leaderboard = {model: [] for model in models_to_train}

for model in models_to_train:
    predictor_solo_model = TabularPredictor(label='count', eval_metric='root_mean_squared_error').fit(
        train.drop(['registered', 'casual'], axis=1),
        time_limit=150,
        presets='best_quality',
        hyperparameters={model: {}}
    )

    best_model = predictor_solo_model.model_best
    solo_model_leaderboard[model] = (best_model, predictor_solo_model.leaderboard()['score_val'][0])

    prediction_solo_model = predictor_solo_model.predict(test)
    prediction_solo_model[prediction_solo_model < 0] = 0
    submission_solo_model = pd.read_csv('sampleSubmission.csv')
    submission_solo_model["count"] = prediction_solo_model
    filename = f"solo_{model}.csv"
    submission_solo_model.to_csv(filename, index=False)
    !kaggle competitions submit -c bike-sharing-demand -f {filename} -m "solo model {model}"
